00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:34.710
politics, and art history.

00:01:34.710 --> 00:01:37.150
Let me give you some examples.

00:01:37.150 --> 00:01:41.240
Latour's studies of Louie
Pasteur and laboratories

00:01:41.240 --> 00:01:45.620
have deepened our insight
into how science is practiced,

00:01:45.620 --> 00:01:49.640
examining not just the data
of scientific knowledge,

00:01:49.640 --> 00:01:53.750
but the social processes by
which that data is understood

00:01:53.750 --> 00:01:56.700
by both scientists
and laypeople.

00:01:56.700 --> 00:02:00.000
Latour is the key founder of
actor network theory, which

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.030
argues that in order to
understand our larger systems,

00:02:03.030 --> 00:02:06.240
whether a city, or a
nation, or a planet,

00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:08.590
we must examine
the relationships

00:02:08.590 --> 00:02:10.639
between multiple entities.

00:02:10.639 --> 00:02:12.720
We must understand
the interactions

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:15.080
between different
people to be sure,

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:18.980
but we must also understand
how people, plants, animals,

00:02:18.980 --> 00:02:22.540
objects, and places
influence each other.

00:02:22.540 --> 00:02:25.220
Actor network theory
has left its mark

00:02:25.220 --> 00:02:29.440
on fields ranging from ancient
history to public health.

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:32.400
When applied to a field
like urban planning,

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:34.650
actor network theory
takes the structures

00:02:34.650 --> 00:02:37.360
that shape human
interaction and thinking

00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:39.260
and makes them visible.

00:02:39.260 --> 00:02:42.070
Latour's illuminating
multimedia essay,

00:02:42.070 --> 00:02:46.000
"Paris the Invisible City"
inspects the city with just

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.850
such a lens, zooming down
to the level of street signs

00:02:49.850 --> 00:02:53.610
and traffic lights to
uncover, as Latour puts it,

00:02:53.610 --> 00:02:56.540
the Parises within Paris.

00:02:56.540 --> 00:03:00.060
Latour invites us to examine
our assumptions and frameworks

00:03:00.060 --> 00:03:01.240
with rigor.

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:04.150
He questions what it
means to be modern

00:03:04.150 --> 00:03:08.070
and complicates the way
we categorize objects.

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:10.930
Today, Latour will
speak to us on a topic

00:03:10.930 --> 00:03:15.440
both urgent and colossal, how
do we make sense of ourselves

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:20.190
and our planet in an age
of rapid climate change?

00:03:20.190 --> 00:03:24.930
President Obama calls planet
warming terrifying, not just

00:03:24.930 --> 00:03:27.580
for what it means for
ocean acidity, ice

00:03:27.580 --> 00:03:30.560
caps, and ecosystems,
but for, as he puts it,

00:03:30.560 --> 00:03:34.870
and I quote him, "the strains
on cultures, on civilizations,

00:03:34.870 --> 00:03:37.180
on nations."

00:03:37.180 --> 00:03:40.080
And that is why we
need Bruno Latour.

00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:43.510
We have heard over and over
about what climate change might

00:03:43.510 --> 00:03:47.150
mean for our national security
or our foreign policy,

00:03:47.150 --> 00:03:51.370
but we do not stop to think
often enough about its impact

00:03:51.370 --> 00:03:53.700
on culture and society.

00:03:53.700 --> 00:03:58.050
We live in an age many have
called the Anthropocene,

00:03:58.050 --> 00:04:00.230
meaning an era in
which humanity has

00:04:00.230 --> 00:04:03.600
shaped the planet on
an unprecedented scale.

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:08.040
How can we square our previous
notions of human agency

00:04:08.040 --> 00:04:12.100
with the current reality
and probable future in which

00:04:12.100 --> 00:04:14.960
human inflicted
damage to the planet

00:04:14.960 --> 00:04:17.930
overwhelms human
capacity to solve

00:04:17.930 --> 00:04:20.260
the problems we have created?

00:04:20.260 --> 00:04:23.820
How will our previous ideas
about nature, religion,

00:04:23.820 --> 00:04:25.920
and science hold up?

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:28.590
And how must we reassess them?

00:04:28.590 --> 00:04:30.790
Those are exactly the
types of questions

00:04:30.790 --> 00:04:34.840
that Bruno Latour can help
us ask and begin to answer.

00:04:34.840 --> 00:04:37.500
His new work, which we
will discuss tonight,

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:39.730
wrestles with
these timely issues

00:04:39.730 --> 00:04:43.990
across the disciplines of
anthropology, science, history,

00:04:43.990 --> 00:04:45.780
and political theory.

00:04:45.780 --> 00:04:47.900
