identical to the mix
of quarks, and gluons,

00:55:54.730 --> 00:55:56.890
and you hit a couple
of protons together.

00:55:56.890 --> 00:55:58.570
And the fluid, and
the turbulence,

00:55:58.570 --> 00:56:00.290
and all that happens
at the micro-scale

00:56:00.290 --> 00:56:04.660
actually is the same thing as
the turbulence of space-time

00:56:04.660 --> 00:56:05.970
around a black hole.

00:56:05.970 --> 00:56:07.490
Even one of the
things that Einstein

00:56:07.490 --> 00:56:10.710
hated about his own theory was
that it predicted black holes.

00:56:10.710 --> 00:56:13.110
He didn't like that, because
black holes indicated

00:56:13.110 --> 00:56:15.420
the very limits of
that theory it's said

00:56:15.420 --> 00:56:20.410
at the center of a black hole
all of our laws come to naught.

00:56:20.410 --> 00:56:23.360
Indeed, the singularity
there isn't even part

00:56:23.360 --> 00:56:28.070
of the space and time which
we are trying to characterize.

00:56:28.070 --> 00:56:32.120
So there isn't the idea
that you've sometimes

00:56:32.120 --> 00:56:36.610
discussed about the big
as being the overlapping

00:56:36.610 --> 00:56:38.830
aspect of the
smalls, that we don't

00:56:38.830 --> 00:56:43.270
have such a simple assembly, but
rather even the idea of scale

00:56:43.270 --> 00:56:46.850
is something that depends on how
we're invoking it is something

00:56:46.850 --> 00:56:50.050
that I think, in
contemporary physics,

00:56:50.050 --> 00:56:56.020
has actually a productive analog
in that the big and the small,

00:56:56.020 --> 00:56:58.990
neither is prior that
the big is in the small

00:56:58.990 --> 00:57:03.440
and the small is in the
big in interesting ways.

00:57:03.440 --> 00:57:06.250
The third and last
point I wanted to get at

00:57:06.250 --> 00:57:09.310
has to do with a long-time
theme of your work,

00:57:09.310 --> 00:57:12.260
which I find I'm
very sympathetic to,

00:57:12.260 --> 00:57:15.580
and that is the relationship
of nature and culture, at least

00:57:15.580 --> 00:57:21.990
the idea of trying to get
around the continuous obsession

00:57:21.990 --> 00:57:27.150
with an opposition of nature
and culture, Phusis and Nomos.

00:57:27.150 --> 00:57:30.620
And among environmental
historians

00:57:30.620 --> 00:57:34.900
and among philosopher literary
theorists, Raymond Williams,

00:57:34.900 --> 00:57:40.769
or Cronin, the idea that--
for instance, Raymond Williams

00:57:40.769 --> 00:57:42.435
talks about the city
and the countryside

00:57:42.435 --> 00:57:45.410
and opposes their opposition,
another one of those

00:57:45.410 --> 00:57:48.620
terribly mischievous
ideas that has backed up

00:57:48.620 --> 00:57:52.330
a lot of right-wing
rhetoric of the countryside

00:57:52.330 --> 00:57:54.040
as the pure, the
authentic, and the prior

00:57:54.040 --> 00:57:59.390
in the city as the artifactual,
later development and rather

00:57:59.390 --> 00:58:01.790
to see these as
producing one another.

00:58:04.730 --> 00:58:07.700
I think that perhaps
this idea of thinking

00:58:07.700 --> 00:58:13.160
of nature and culture
together put me in mind

00:58:13.160 --> 00:58:16.420
to think one of the most famous
passages of William James

00:58:16.420 --> 00:58:19.530
where he's talking about truth.

00:58:19.530 --> 00:58:23.090
But if we were to swap
out his picture of truth

00:58:23.090 --> 00:58:26.410
for that of nature, perhaps
we could reread or misread

00:58:26.410 --> 00:58:29.360
that paragraph,
something like this.

00:58:29.360 --> 00:58:32.740
"The trail of the human serpent
is thus over everything.

00:58:32.740 --> 00:58:36.190
Nature independent, nature
that we find merely,

00:58:36.190 --> 00:58:39.010
nature no longer
malleable to human need,

00:58:39.010 --> 00:58:40.660
nature incorrigible.

00:58:40.660 --> 00:58:43.595
In a word, such nature exists,
indeed super-abundantly,

00:58:43.595 --> 00:58:45.530
or is supposed to exist.

00:58:45.530 --> 00:58:48.990
But then it means only the
dead heart of the living tree.

00:58:48.990 --> 00:58:51.520
And its being there means
only that nature also

00:58:51.520 --> 00:58:53.790
has its paleontology.

00:58:53.790 --> 00:58:56.870
Its prescription may
grow stiff with years

00:58:56.870 --> 00:58:59.870
of veteran service
petrified in men's regard

00:58:59.870 --> 00:59:01.670
by sheer antiquity."

00:59:01.670 --> 00:59:04.870
And that idea that we face
a nature that's constantly

00:59:04.870 --> 00:59:07.200
in motion, all the
interesting parts of nature

00:59:07.200 --> 00:59:09.990
are not stable, not
fixed, but something

00:59:09.990 --> 00:59:15.220
that we are modifying
sometimes for the great worse

00:59:15.220 --> 00:59:17.260
and sometimes for
the great better,

00:59:17.260 --> 00:59:20.700
but that these technical
lands, these technical oceans,

00:59:20.700 --> 00:59:25.340
these technical atmospheres
that we live in give us

00:59:25.340 --> 00:59:28.450
an implication in the
world that does indeed

00:59:28.450 --> 00:59:32.130
offer the possibility of
thinking politics in a very

00:59:32.130 --> 00:59:36.280
different way, one which not
only in anthropology, but also

00:59:36.280 --> 00:59:38.510
in our art work,
in our literature,

00:59:38.510 --> 00:59:41.910
in our environmental policies,
and environmental justice,

00:59:41.910 --> 00:59:50.330
puts us into a world that is
not stable, but unfolding.

00:59:50.330 --> 00:59:51.760
- Thank you, Peter, very much.

00:59:51.760 --> 00:59:55.840
And thank you so much for
stressing the issue of scale

00:59:55.840 --> 01:00:00.100
as being what I think
you call Bruno constantly

01:00:00.100 --> 01:00:02.790
redistributive and folding.

01:00:02.790 --> 01:00:05.590
And I think that it's so
important, particularly

01:00:05.590 --> 01:00:08.220
when we talk about
globalization, because scale

01:00:08.220 --> 01:00:09.180
is not about size.

01:00:09.180 --> 01:00:11.470
It's about complexity
and interrelationships

01:00:11.470 --> 01:00:12.910
and iterability.

01:00:12.910 --> 01:00:17.160
So that notion of enfolding that
you ended with, Peter, was I

01:00:17.160 --> 01:00:19.020
think very provocative
and very useful.

01:00:19.020 --> 01:00:20.230
Thank you very much.

01:00:20.230 --> 01:00:21.240
Diane.

01:00:21.240 --> 01:00:23.870
- OK, maybe I'll pick up
on some of those issues.

01:00:23.870 --> 01:00:26.840
It's a really great honor
to be here, a pleasure,

01:00:26.840 --> 01:00:31.840
I'm very daunted to be on
this table here with you.

01:00:31.840 --> 01:00:34.640
I guess I want to say that the
main issue for me that you're

01:00:34.640 --> 01:00:37.450
addressing in your
presentation and the materials

01:00:37.450 --> 01:00:42.750
that you shared with us is the
question what is, or should,

01:00:42.750 --> 01:00:47.184
or could, be the politics
of the Anthropocene?

01:00:47.184 --> 01:00:48.600
And I think that's
a question that

01:00:48.600 --> 01:00:52.380
needs to be pondered not just
in terms of individual actions,

01:00:52.380 --> 01:00:55.140
but with respect to the
governance institutions that

01:00:55.140 --> 01:00:59.020
help enable our collective
future so in that sense,

01:00:59.020 --> 01:01:05.440
I see today's talk as raising
the possibility of the fact

01:01:05.440 --> 01:01:09.590
that we need to develop new
forms of sovereignty, that

01:01:09.590 --> 01:01:12.430
is new governance
regimes, in order

01:01:12.430 --> 01:01:16.570
to be able to connect the dots
between land, Earth, globe,

01:01:16.570 --> 01:01:18.030
and Gaia.

01:01:18.030 --> 01:01:21.424
Now, I know that already puts
me in a more optimistic camp

01:01:21.424 --> 01:01:23.340
than you, Bruno, because
the title of the talk

01:01:23.340 --> 01:01:25.620
was on not connecting the dots.

01:01:25.620 --> 01:01:28.360
And I do agree that part of
the concern that you have

01:01:28.360 --> 01:01:30.340
and that I share
derives from the view

01:01:30.340 --> 01:01:34.220
that current global governance
arrangements, something brought

01:01:34.220 --> 01:01:36.410
to life in the Paris
and Kigali agreements

01:01:36.410 --> 01:01:40.730
in the last couple weeks,
build upon and, in fact,

01:01:40.730 --> 01:01:43.860
reify the nation state as
a primary starting point

01:01:43.860 --> 01:01:46.560
for sovereignty arrangements.

01:01:46.560 --> 01:01:49.360
You thus are clearly arguing
that the embodied power

01:01:49.360 --> 01:01:51.320
of the nation state
has enabled many

01:01:51.320 --> 01:01:54.220
of the ecologically
destructive practices for which

01:01:54.220 --> 01:01:56.800
new forms of global
government agreements

01:01:56.800 --> 01:02:00.440
are now being sought in
order to clean up the mess.

01:02:00.440 --> 01:02:02.960
You also rightly argue
that when decisions

01:02:02.960 --> 01:02:06.530
remain in the hands of nation
states, even those joining

01:02:06.530 --> 01:02:10.060
in global agglomeration, the
chances of truly addressing

01:02:10.060 --> 01:02:13.370
the risks associated with the
ever-more-destructive march

01:02:13.370 --> 01:02:17.220
of modernity are
indeed quite limited.

01:02:17.220 --> 01:02:19.360
And we all here know of
the fraught debate that

01:02:19.360 --> 01:02:22.660
has and will continue to
ensue in so-called modernized

01:02:22.660 --> 01:02:27.290
countries now lead discussions
about environmental regulations

01:02:27.290 --> 01:02:29.860
that keep their own
historical gains

01:02:29.860 --> 01:02:34.610
and the Earth's losses-- gains
come through colonization

01:02:34.610 --> 01:02:36.910
and imperialism, et cetera.

01:02:36.910 --> 01:02:39.520
They are kept in place even
as these same countries are

01:02:39.520 --> 01:02:41.810
imposing high barriers to
other countries who are

01:02:41.810 --> 01:02:45.440
desperate to become modernized.

01:02:45.440 --> 01:02:48.130
So but I want to suggest that
one way out of the conundrum,

01:02:48.130 --> 01:02:50.010
or maybe we can talk
about this hopefully,

01:02:50.010 --> 01:02:53.470
is to imagine an alternative
form of sovereignty that is not

01:02:53.470 --> 01:02:55.800
tied so directly
to the nation state

01:02:55.800 --> 01:02:58.870
and that, in fact, recognizes
other territorialities

01:02:58.870 --> 01:03:02.280
of governance and
political practice,

01:03:02.280 --> 01:03:05.460
particularly those smaller
than the nation as well as

01:03:05.460 --> 01:03:06.790
the globe.

01:03:06.790 --> 01:03:08.970
I put this possibility
on the table coming

01:03:08.970 --> 01:03:12.840
from my own experiences
in an urban design school

01:03:12.840 --> 01:03:15.200
and as the author of a book
called Urban Leviathan.

01:03:15.200 --> 01:03:17.692
So when you put Hobbes'
picture up there,

01:03:17.692 --> 01:03:19.990
you had me right there.

01:03:19.990 --> 01:03:22.720
And I teach classes about
urban governance that

01:03:22.720 --> 01:03:24.810
encourage students
to think not only

01:03:24.810 --> 01:03:27.750
about the city as a site of
growing environmental risk,

01:03:27.750 --> 01:03:30.870
but also about the city as a
source or site of resilience

01:03:30.870 --> 01:03:33.960
in which new spatial
designs and even art

01:03:33.960 --> 01:03:37.390
projects from the
microterritorial level

01:03:37.390 --> 01:03:41.380
of the building and the
street, to the city,

01:03:41.380 --> 01:03:45.870
to the macroterritorial scale
of the city and its hinterlands,

01:03:45.870 --> 01:03:48.220
can provide new
ways of confronting

01:03:48.220 --> 01:03:51.850
contemporary
ecological challenges.

01:03:51.850 --> 01:03:53.880
Now, it's obvious the
changing conditions

01:03:53.880 --> 01:03:57.110
at the scale of a city clearly
will not address all the risks

01:03:57.110 --> 01:03:59.390
to the Earth that
are hurtling us

01:03:59.390 --> 01:04:03.520
towards an unstable and
darker ecological future.

01:04:03.520 --> 01:04:07.220
However, I would say that
activities undertaken in cities

01:04:07.220 --> 01:04:11.360
have an overwhelming impact
on aggregate Earth conditions

01:04:11.360 --> 01:04:14.710
unless they might serve as a
more productive starting point

01:04:14.710 --> 01:04:18.390
for new agreements that
could have global impact.

01:04:18.390 --> 01:04:20.530
Likewise, cities
themselves are connected

01:04:20.530 --> 01:04:24.430
through networks that
straddle the globe thus making

01:04:24.430 --> 01:04:26.710
it possible to have
two-way conversations

01:04:26.710 --> 01:04:28.870
about the local and the global.

01:04:28.870 --> 01:04:31.520
And actually, perhaps
most significantly for me

01:04:31.520 --> 01:04:34.870
as a historical
urban sociologist,

01:04:34.870 --> 01:04:37.630
there are historical, social,
and cultural differences

01:04:37.630 --> 01:04:40.340
associated with national
and state sovereignty

01:04:40.340 --> 01:04:43.560
that get in the way of
cross-national agreements.

01:04:43.560 --> 01:04:45.610
But the experience
of living in cities

01:04:45.610 --> 01:04:48.120
holds the promise
or the potential

01:04:48.120 --> 01:04:50.420
to create elective
affinity among peoples

01:04:50.420 --> 01:04:53.200
across many different
national contexts.

01:04:53.200 --> 01:04:55.020
In that sense, the
urban experience

01:04:55.020 --> 01:04:58.060
could provide a basis for
developing a common language

01:04:58.060 --> 01:04:59.970
about the embeddedness
of the human

01:04:59.970 --> 01:05:03.770
and the non-human experience
that remains elusive at larger

01:05:03.770 --> 01:05:05.880
territorial scales.

01:05:05.880 --> 01:05:08.890
People can really
articulate and tangibly

01:05:08.890 --> 01:05:12.800
grasp what it means
to survive or thrive

01:05:12.800 --> 01:05:16.180
ecologically or otherwise
at the level of the street

01:05:16.180 --> 01:05:18.080
and at the level
of the city in ways

01:05:18.080 --> 01:05:20.490
that they won't at other scales.

01:05:20.490 --> 01:05:23.790
As such, I would say that
the city is and should

01:05:23.790 --> 01:05:29.250
be considered the body politic
of Anthropocene, if you will,

01:05:29.250 --> 01:05:31.710
one that literally
unites bodies in politics

01:05:31.710 --> 01:05:34.620
around the grounded
experience of everyday life,

01:05:34.620 --> 01:05:38.750
almost a throwback to
earlier pre-modern period

01:05:38.750 --> 01:05:42.680
before the advent of the
Westphalian national state,

01:05:42.680 --> 01:05:46.930
scaled up the territoriality
as a political allegiance,

01:05:46.930 --> 01:05:49.590
and when it was
cities or city states

01:05:49.590 --> 01:05:52.020
were the nodes and
networks through which

01:05:52.020 --> 01:05:56.660
the global economy and the
modern project emerged.

01:05:56.660 --> 01:06:00.190
So let me end my remarks
by recasting these,

01:06:00.190 --> 01:06:02.050
and they're your ideas
as well, I would say,

01:06:02.050 --> 01:06:06.220
they're very much inspired
by what you presented today,

01:06:06.220 --> 01:06:07.680
through the lens of sovereignty.

01:06:07.680 --> 01:06:10.780
I want to come back to that very
critical and important concept

01:06:10.780 --> 01:06:13.760
that Bruno has put on the table.

01:06:13.760 --> 01:06:16.860
I think it's obvious
that I want to think

01:06:16.860 --> 01:06:19.710
more broadly about
sovereignty relying

01:06:19.710 --> 01:06:23.400
as much on the lens of scholars
like Benedict Anderson, who

01:06:23.400 --> 01:06:26.150
defined nationalism, and
thus national sovereignty,

01:06:26.150 --> 01:06:30.210
as an imagined community,
emanating from citizens

01:06:30.210 --> 01:06:32.860
and their meaningful
connections to each other

01:06:32.860 --> 01:06:35.990
rather than seeing nationalism
as an ideology imposed

01:06:35.990 --> 01:06:39.940
by a national state in the
service of sovereign power.

01:06:39.940 --> 01:06:41.740
I also want us to
consider that there

01:06:41.740 --> 01:06:44.280
may exist alternative
territorial scales

01:06:44.280 --> 01:06:47.470
of experience and
identity that can forge

01:06:47.470 --> 01:06:51.200
an imagined community, or an
alternative territorial form

01:06:51.200 --> 01:06:53.440
of sovereignty, or even
overlapping sovereignties,

01:06:53.440 --> 01:06:56.610
as one of your slides
mentioned the concept,

01:06:56.610 --> 01:06:59.840
capable of advancing
an ecological politics

01:06:59.840 --> 01:07:02.170
for the future.

01:07:02.170 --> 01:07:05.920
Finally, I want to suggest that
in order to discover and reveal

01:07:05.920 --> 01:07:09.780
these new imagined communities
and any new territorial

01:07:09.780 --> 01:07:12.290
forms of sovereignty
they might enable,

01:07:12.290 --> 01:07:15.120
we need to be more
creative in our documenting

01:07:15.120 --> 01:07:18.320
and understanding of the
scales and modalities

01:07:18.320 --> 01:07:20.860
of the actually
lived experienced,

01:07:20.860 --> 01:07:23.090
of the actually lived space.

01:07:23.090 --> 01:07:26.150
We must begin to understand
the phenomenology of how

01:07:26.150 --> 01:07:29.540
individuals might
collectively translate

01:07:29.540 --> 01:07:31.790
the experience of
local conditions

01:07:31.790 --> 01:07:36.170
into a larger ecological
ethos, which itself can serve

01:07:36.170 --> 01:07:40.130
as a basis for connecting
to the Earth and the globe,

01:07:40.130 --> 01:07:43.480
but do so through the
embrace of the local

01:07:43.480 --> 01:07:46.640
as a site from which a new
politics of sovereignty

01:07:46.640 --> 01:07:49.270
might emanate.

01:07:49.270 --> 01:07:52.660
- Diane, thank you very much,
again, the question of scale.

01:07:52.660 --> 01:07:56.355
A scale comes up again
like the prominent theme

01:07:56.355 --> 01:07:59.820
of what you're talking,
the scale of forms,

01:07:59.820 --> 01:08:01.860
smaller than the
nation, as you put it.

01:08:01.860 --> 01:08:05.530
And you talk about the
city here as a form

01:08:05.530 --> 01:08:09.580
of alternative
sovereignty or contra

01:08:09.580 --> 01:08:11.230
sovereignty of some kind.

01:08:11.230 --> 01:08:18.450
It seems to me that really
the title comes alive here,

01:08:18.450 --> 01:08:22.750
because maybe the
city and its forms

01:08:22.750 --> 01:08:28.130
of non-imperial sovereignty,
or non-hegemonic sovereignty

01:08:28.130 --> 01:08:31.479
that you suggest, is
because the cities may

01:08:31.479 --> 01:08:34.620
be dots that are not connected.

01:08:34.620 --> 01:08:37.160
So they're connecting the dot.

01:08:37.160 --> 01:08:39.189
The dot are the
cities, which are not

01:08:39.189 --> 01:08:44.290
connected in through the hole
in either part nor whole,

01:08:44.290 --> 01:08:47.319
but they are kind of
iterative networks

01:08:47.319 --> 01:08:49.710
of particular relationalities.

01:08:49.710 --> 01:08:53.220
So I think that you
certainly put on the table

01:08:53.220 --> 01:08:57.470
another way of
thinking of the city

01:08:57.470 --> 01:09:02.264
as a sort of connected
network and its agencies.

01:09:02.264 --> 01:09:03.680
I don't know whether
that actually

01:09:03.680 --> 01:09:06.840
fits with Benedict
Anderson at all,

01:09:06.840 --> 01:09:10.330
because he is so immersed
in the soup of the nation

01:09:10.330 --> 01:09:11.569
and its containment.

01:09:11.569 --> 01:09:13.109
He needs that containment.

01:09:13.109 --> 01:09:15.850
But thank you very much for
these provocative remarks.

01:09:15.850 --> 01:09:18.170
And now, we turn to Bruno.

01:09:18.170 --> 01:09:19.260
- What is my role now?

01:09:19.260 --> 01:09:21.720
- Now, your role, Bruno,
is to basically talk

01:09:21.720 --> 01:09:24.580
a little, entertain us
with some responses,

01:09:24.580 --> 01:09:26.859
and then we can open up.

01:09:26.859 --> 01:09:28.640
So your role is that
of the entertainer.

01:09:28.640 --> 01:09:33.880
- I'm starting to be
