- OK, so I'll start with Diane.

01:09:51.470 --> 01:09:53.550
I think one of the
interesting things

01:09:53.550 --> 01:09:56.820
is to explore collectively the
notion of overlapping entities,

01:09:56.820 --> 01:09:59.687
because if they overlap,
actually in the simulation,

01:09:59.687 --> 01:10:01.270
the cities were very
important, and we

01:10:01.270 --> 01:10:04.206
presented as such, and
the network of cities,

01:10:04.206 --> 01:10:05.580
of course, an
ecological question

01:10:05.580 --> 01:10:09.110
is sometimes much more advanced
than many nation states.

01:10:09.110 --> 01:10:12.650
But it's still a problem of
scale, which is small and big.

01:10:12.650 --> 01:10:16.220
It doesn't capture overlapping--
and overlapping means

01:10:16.220 --> 01:10:20.178
that it's like a Hobbesian
argument for what

01:10:20.178 --> 01:10:23.590
is the ensemble, so to speak,
of representing ourselves

01:10:23.590 --> 01:10:26.460
plus all the
millions and billions

01:10:26.460 --> 01:10:30.780
of microbes and bacteria
composing something

01:10:30.780 --> 01:10:35.050
which has no clear boundaries,
which we call a human body.

01:10:35.050 --> 01:10:36.500
You talk about the body politic.

01:10:36.500 --> 01:10:38.607
We don't know much
about what the body is.

01:10:38.607 --> 01:10:40.940
So that metaphor of the body
politic is a complex thing.

01:10:40.940 --> 01:10:42.420
But what is
interesting is the need

01:10:42.420 --> 01:10:45.920
to reinvent just at the
time when people would want

01:10:45.920 --> 01:10:48.900
precisely to go back to
the notion of sovereignty,

01:10:48.900 --> 01:10:52.740
and that's connected to
the question of Homi, which

01:10:52.740 --> 01:11:01.340
is the border protection
arrives everywhere

01:11:01.340 --> 01:11:05.161
just at the time of
ecological crisis

01:11:05.161 --> 01:11:06.660
where it nothing
in physics probably

01:11:06.660 --> 01:11:09.560
but it means nothing in
biology, and it means not much

01:11:09.560 --> 01:11:10.780
in the future of politics.

01:11:10.780 --> 01:11:16.000
But we need to guarantee
what Peter Sloterdijk called

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:18.110
the immunological
condition of existence

01:11:18.110 --> 01:11:21.920
as well, because whenever we
talk about nature as Sloterdijk

01:11:21.920 --> 01:11:25.880
says, nature is not a
place where we inhabit.

01:11:25.880 --> 01:11:28.360
It's a place where
other things happen,

01:11:28.360 --> 01:11:31.941
but certainly not life forms
in the concept of nature,

01:11:31.941 --> 01:11:32.440
of course.

01:11:32.440 --> 01:11:34.850
So it's a very
complicated question here

01:11:34.850 --> 01:11:38.440
is how can we retain
the notion of protection

01:11:38.440 --> 01:11:42.240
and multiply the type of
overlapping sovereignty.

01:11:42.240 --> 01:11:45.130
I have one good example,
a small example,

01:11:45.130 --> 01:11:49.340
which is the election in
Holland where they have

01:11:49.340 --> 01:11:50.780
a double system of election.

01:11:50.780 --> 01:11:54.140
We elect the Congress
and parliamentary people,

01:11:54.140 --> 01:11:59.950
but they also elect the
[INAUDIBLE] or something

01:11:59.950 --> 01:12:04.600
like that, who is the
one representing water.

01:12:04.600 --> 01:12:06.040
And actually, the
two authorities

01:12:06.040 --> 01:12:09.560
have the same sort
of legitimacy.

01:12:09.560 --> 01:12:11.020
And they occupy the same space.

01:12:11.020 --> 01:12:12.790
But one is for
humans, so to speak,

01:12:12.790 --> 01:12:14.320
and the other one is for water.

01:12:14.320 --> 01:12:16.650
Water is fairly important,
as you know, in Holland.

01:12:16.650 --> 01:12:21.327
And it's a sort of necessary
thing to have these two powers,

01:12:21.327 --> 01:12:22.410
so to speak.

01:12:22.410 --> 01:12:25.030
But it's interesting
that on the same space,

01:12:25.030 --> 01:12:28.400
the overlapping is possible
and many, of course,

01:12:28.400 --> 01:12:29.790
other innovations.

01:12:29.790 --> 01:12:32.660
The question is precisely
to avoid to say, well,

01:12:32.660 --> 01:12:33.610
borders are finished.

01:12:33.610 --> 01:12:36.240
And we can never go to
the global and [INAUDIBLE]

01:12:36.240 --> 01:12:39.320
sort of archaic
hillbilly people are

01:12:39.320 --> 01:12:41.700
attached to the local scene.

01:12:41.700 --> 01:12:44.930
There is an immunological
principle in the boundaries.

01:12:44.930 --> 01:12:47.530
But it's not necessarily
linked with the notion

01:12:47.530 --> 01:12:49.260
of border protection.

01:12:49.260 --> 01:12:51.660
Now, of course, it is
linked to the nation state.

01:12:51.660 --> 01:12:54.840
This is the European
problem, par excellence,

01:12:54.840 --> 01:13:00.290
and Europe had invented a very
subtle and complicated system

01:13:00.290 --> 01:13:03.240
of overlapping sovereignty
until the bloody Brits tried

01:13:03.240 --> 01:13:07.770
to get out of it, which is
amusing, because they are also

01:13:07.770 --> 01:13:12.120
the ones who invented the global
sort of regime of the globe.

01:13:12.120 --> 01:13:15.070
So it's very telling that the
first country which really

01:13:15.070 --> 01:13:18.550
invented the global market is
also the one who suddenly says,

01:13:18.550 --> 01:13:24.240
let's go back to the queen
yacht, which is [INAUDIBLE].

01:13:24.240 --> 01:13:27.610
And of course, I answered
Peter and completely agree.

01:13:27.610 --> 01:13:30.310
Actually, I'm not
interested in the way--

01:13:30.310 --> 01:13:33.370
am interested in a strange
way with some concept

01:13:33.370 --> 01:13:35.930
of political philosophy
have been transported

01:13:35.930 --> 01:13:38.850
into a plotted notion of
physics, which of course, has

01:13:38.850 --> 01:13:41.950
no relation whatsoever
with your practice

01:13:41.950 --> 01:13:45.610
and the multiplicity of
entity by physicists.

01:13:45.610 --> 01:13:47.580
But it become the
sort of-- when we

01:13:47.580 --> 01:13:51.080
talk about nature and
objects, we mostly

01:13:51.080 --> 01:13:54.190
sort of use a mixture
of things which

01:13:54.190 --> 01:13:56.300
can be completely
badly understood

01:13:56.300 --> 01:13:59.680
Newtonian physics, but a
lot of political philosophy,

01:13:59.680 --> 01:14:04.190
especially on the notion
of inertness of matter.

01:14:04.190 --> 01:14:06.890
And this inertness of matter,
which of course, historians,

01:14:06.890 --> 01:14:09.960
especially in your department,
have studied for a long time

01:14:09.960 --> 01:14:13.390
is a much more complicated
history than that.

01:14:13.390 --> 01:14:18.070
But it is the, how could I say?

01:14:18.070 --> 01:14:22.230
The common ways in which
we understand nature.

01:14:22.230 --> 01:14:23.710
And I'm interested
in what you say,

01:14:23.710 --> 01:14:27.570
I mean, because of a terrorist.

01:14:27.570 --> 01:14:30.550
In my experience, it
is the French state,

01:14:30.550 --> 01:14:32.880
and I think there is
some connection here

01:14:32.880 --> 01:14:37.930
as Sloterdijk says again,
it's an autoimmune disease.

01:14:37.930 --> 01:14:43.410
And people are fed back on
police, and army, and borders

01:14:43.410 --> 01:14:47.159
as the simplest way to-- it's
sort of benediction, police

01:14:47.159 --> 01:14:49.600
and state.

01:14:49.600 --> 01:14:52.420
We have no idea what politics
is, but police and state,

01:14:52.420 --> 01:14:53.110
that we know.

01:14:53.110 --> 01:14:58.550
It's the last thing which seems
like a state and authority.

01:14:58.550 --> 01:15:00.290
And in France,
it's exactly that.

01:15:00.290 --> 01:15:03.110
There is absolutely not
politics left except police.

01:15:03.110 --> 01:15:08.140
I mean, the police are actually
striking right now today.

01:15:08.140 --> 01:15:11.020
So maybe even that, [INAUDIBLE].

01:15:11.020 --> 01:15:16.290
So the terrorist was a sort of
a gift of God, literally a gift

01:15:16.290 --> 01:15:19.490
of God for the remnant
of what the Westphalian

01:15:19.490 --> 01:15:21.940
state is supposed to be,
in some sort of sense.

01:15:21.940 --> 01:15:24.140
But it's not at all
the third attractor,

01:15:24.140 --> 01:15:26.660
because there is no-- I mean,
maybe I'm probably wrong,

01:15:26.660 --> 01:15:28.840
but there is no
vast contribution

01:15:28.840 --> 01:15:32.380
to the alternative
cosmology, as far as I

01:15:32.380 --> 01:15:34.102
can tell and a
complete indifference

01:15:34.102 --> 01:15:36.310
to the question of ecology,
if I am not wrong, right?

01:15:36.310 --> 01:15:37.640
- No, but it's a negative.

01:15:37.640 --> 01:15:39.670
I'm saying, it's the negative.

01:15:39.670 --> 01:15:42.920
But in a way, you
never know where

01:15:42.920 --> 01:15:44.620
the border is going to be.

01:15:44.620 --> 01:15:47.808
It's that the border is where
the terror act takes place.

01:15:47.808 --> 01:15:50.860
So the borders are
continually changing.

01:15:50.860 --> 01:15:52.630
So it's a negative of that.

01:15:52.630 --> 01:15:57.695
- The direct link there is with
the ecological crisis is with

01:15:57.695 --> 01:16:01.870
immigration, because here the
link is technically-- sorry,

01:16:01.870 --> 01:16:04.720
[INAUDIBLE] crossing boundaries.

01:16:04.720 --> 01:16:07.880
And what do we do with the
crossing of boundaries,

01:16:07.880 --> 01:16:11.340
the walls, is a
key question, which

01:16:11.340 --> 01:16:15.780
is the way in which
most people actually

01:16:15.780 --> 01:16:20.630
get the shock of the ecological
crisis is now from migration.

01:16:20.630 --> 01:16:24.284
And that's where the
link is most interesting.

01:16:24.284 --> 01:16:24.784
Yes ?

01:16:26.230 --> 01:16:29.139
- I'm wondering, and I wanted to
ask you, Bruno, and also Peter,

01:16:29.139 --> 01:16:30.430
because this is your expertise.

01:16:30.430 --> 01:16:32.580
But I'm just
wondering whether it's

01:16:32.580 --> 01:16:34.430
possible to take some
of these concepts

01:16:34.430 --> 01:16:38.020
that we've just been talking
about sovereignty, terror,

01:16:38.020 --> 01:16:43.190
violence, borders, and
use those to think more

01:16:43.190 --> 01:16:45.930
about the natural world
and if that is then

01:16:45.930 --> 01:16:48.000
becomes a discourse
that allows one

01:16:48.000 --> 01:16:50.671
to move back and forth between
the human and the non-human

01:16:50.671 --> 01:16:51.170
in a way.

01:16:51.170 --> 01:16:52.890
I'm not an ecologist.

01:16:52.890 --> 01:16:55.820
But it seems to me that we
could think about plant life,

01:16:55.820 --> 01:17:00.230
or that again, the natural,
I'm getting beyond my pay grade

01:17:00.230 --> 01:17:02.690
here, but to think a
little more about using

01:17:02.690 --> 01:17:04.260
those same sets of concepts.

01:17:04.260 --> 01:17:08.300
Is there some sense
of what we might--

01:17:08.300 --> 01:17:12.230
the equivalent of a sovereignty
within the natural world?

01:17:12.230 --> 01:17:16.280
- Well, the problem I think
is we have too much commerce.

01:17:16.280 --> 01:17:19.050
The truth of it is very
difficult. But as you know,

01:17:19.050 --> 01:17:21.370
sociology was for plants.

01:17:21.370 --> 01:17:23.060
The Department of
Plant Sociology

01:17:23.060 --> 01:17:24.890
still exists in a dark place

01:17:24.890 --> 01:17:25.390
- Right.

01:17:25.390 --> 01:17:26.275
The organism.

01:17:26.275 --> 01:17:28.330
- --in Switzerland.

01:17:28.330 --> 01:17:30.280
But the problem is
precisely to try

01:17:30.280 --> 01:17:32.070
to not connect
the dots, that is,

01:17:32.070 --> 01:17:36.455
not immediately think an
ecosystem is part and whole.

01:17:36.455 --> 01:17:40.230
The resistance, and this
is why it's very important

01:17:40.230 --> 01:17:41.980
to work with
scientists and people

01:17:41.980 --> 01:17:43.880
from humanity and
the social sciences,

01:17:43.880 --> 01:17:46.120
because they can
help everyone to be

01:17:46.120 --> 01:17:49.510
attentive to the speed at
which the metaphor jumps

01:17:49.510 --> 01:17:50.510
from one to the other.

01:17:50.510 --> 01:17:51.310
It's amazing.

01:17:51.310 --> 01:17:53.940
I was amazed by this
book by Tyrrell.

01:17:53.940 --> 01:17:56.310
I mean, he's a good
scientist, and what he says

01:17:56.310 --> 01:17:58.750
is factually very interesting.

01:17:58.750 --> 01:18:01.320
But he has absolutely
no hint that when

01:18:01.320 --> 01:18:03.990
you talk about Gaia
as a tiller, it's

01:18:03.990 --> 01:18:09.090
a huge import of providential
and political thing

01:18:09.090 --> 01:18:11.460
which ruins this argument
and ruins the of course

01:18:11.460 --> 01:18:13.170
the accusations
against the other.

01:18:13.170 --> 01:18:17.450
So we have to be careful,
again, because when we mentioned

01:18:17.450 --> 01:18:19.590
the notion of the
ecological crisis,

01:18:19.590 --> 01:18:22.510
we are very easily lost
by the question of size.

01:18:22.510 --> 01:18:25.570
And the question of size has to
be studied in different ways.

01:18:25.570 --> 01:18:29.180
That's why overlapping entity,
the notion of small and big

01:18:29.180 --> 01:18:31.600
doesn't really work.

01:18:31.600 --> 01:18:34.880
This is why the paper
I sent you, which

01:18:34.880 --> 01:18:36.675
is a bit boring I'm afraid.

01:18:36.675 --> 01:18:37.550
I apologize for that.

01:18:37.550 --> 01:18:42.260
I tried to get into the
argument that Gabrielle Tarde is

01:18:42.260 --> 01:18:43.985
reintroducing the
notion of monad,

01:18:43.985 --> 01:18:45.610
because I think there
is something very

01:18:45.610 --> 01:18:49.180
interesting in the notion of
monad where precisely scale,

01:18:49.180 --> 01:18:51.780
it's not entity plus relation,
but it's something else

01:18:51.780 --> 01:18:52.890
which is at work.

01:18:52.890 --> 01:18:55.880
And one of my
interests in this field

01:18:55.880 --> 01:18:58.620
study I work with was as
scientists is precisely

01:18:58.620 --> 01:19:01.726
to see how far we can
go with them to find

01:19:01.726 --> 01:19:04.100
an alternative and especially,
of course, which is always

01:19:04.100 --> 01:19:09.250
the key, how to represent
visually these masses of data

01:19:09.250 --> 01:19:10.640
we have about this overlapping.

01:19:10.640 --> 01:19:13.070
I mean, it's a very
interesting case of cities,

01:19:13.070 --> 01:19:15.030
because if you begin
to represent a city,

01:19:15.030 --> 01:19:17.270
you actually, of course,
cover the whole-- I mean,

01:19:17.270 --> 01:19:20.240
if it's a big city, you cover
a large part of the world.

01:19:20.240 --> 01:19:21.840
And you don't cover.

01:19:21.840 --> 01:19:22.829
You connect.

01:19:22.829 --> 01:19:24.495
And all of these
overlapping connections

01:19:24.495 --> 01:19:26.410
are actually very
difficult to visualize.

01:19:26.410 --> 01:19:29.860
And now, with big data, I
think it's a major thing

01:19:29.860 --> 01:19:33.030
to do which is how to find
alternative representation.

01:19:33.030 --> 01:19:36.240
And then once we are
equipped with the alternative

01:19:36.240 --> 01:19:39.330
representation, we can begin
to think of sovereignty

01:19:39.330 --> 01:19:41.880
as something
different from the map

01:19:41.880 --> 01:19:47.640
and a non-overlapping,
ex parte entity.

01:19:47.640 --> 01:19:52.440
So it is a very rich combination
of exchange between biologists

01:19:52.440 --> 01:19:55.190
trying to get out of the
notion of the selfish gene,

01:19:55.190 --> 01:19:58.550
for instance, and
political scientists,

01:19:58.550 --> 01:19:59.844
and many other people.

01:19:59.844 --> 01:20:01.510
- I mean, one of the
things that strikes

01:20:01.510 --> 01:20:07.740
me is that many of our
considerations in your paper,

01:20:07.740 --> 01:20:10.660
your presentation, what I
Diane was talking about,

01:20:10.660 --> 01:20:13.060
some of my concerns have
been around individuation.

01:20:13.060 --> 01:20:15.040
What counts as an object?

01:20:15.040 --> 01:20:20.210
And that, in many
fields, has lost

01:20:20.210 --> 01:20:22.060
the sense of an
eternal stability,

01:20:22.060 --> 01:20:24.930
that there is a
well-defined boundary

01:20:24.930 --> 01:20:27.050
interior versus exterior.

01:20:27.050 --> 01:20:30.740
I mean, in politics the
lowest possible position

01:20:30.740 --> 01:20:33.470
you could have would be to
say that you can solve this

01:20:33.470 --> 01:20:35.400
by building a wall,
as somebody said.

01:20:38.500 --> 01:20:42.800
But that in fact, there are ways
in which our communities are

01:20:42.800 --> 01:20:45.330
configured differently for
all of the different things

01:20:45.330 --> 01:20:46.020
that we do.

01:20:46.020 --> 01:20:47.900
The way we distribute
water is not the same

01:20:47.900 --> 01:20:49.960
as the way we deal
with electricity,

01:20:49.960 --> 01:20:51.090
the way we handle food.

01:20:51.090 --> 01:20:55.490
I mean, the connectivities,
the boundaries are constantly

01:20:55.490 --> 01:21:00.010
fluctuating even at a particular
time, let alone overtime.

01:21:00.010 --> 01:21:03.360
And even the objects,
the organs of our body.

01:21:03.360 --> 01:21:04.902
We can see our heart is a pump.

01:21:04.902 --> 01:21:06.610
But now we know it's
much more than that.

01:21:06.610 --> 01:21:09.090
It has a biochemical function,
an electrical function,

01:21:09.090 --> 01:21:11.488
many other things,.

01:21:11.488 --> 01:21:17.480
Or the stomach, or hormones,
or any of our bodily systems

01:21:17.480 --> 01:21:21.170
are not as localized as we
once wished to imagine them.

01:21:21.170 --> 01:21:24.390
And I think a lot of
the debates in ecology

01:21:24.390 --> 01:21:25.390
have that same function.

01:21:25.390 --> 01:21:29.170
It's like, what is
the relevant system?

01:21:29.170 --> 01:21:32.180
And that doesn't
have a unique answer,

01:21:32.180 --> 01:21:34.020
even at a particular time.

01:21:34.020 --> 01:21:37.480
It's not just that it used to
be local and now it's global.

01:21:37.480 --> 01:21:40.789
It's that it was always
all these different things.

01:21:40.789 --> 01:21:42.830
- I think you're completely
right that the notion

01:21:42.830 --> 01:21:46.290
of individuation is
a key thing, right?

01:21:46.290 --> 01:21:48.040
It's very interesting
to see that happened

01:21:48.040 --> 01:21:53.040
in all sort of places, in ants,
as well as in cells, as well

01:21:53.040 --> 01:21:55.680
as in nation states.

01:21:55.680 --> 01:22:00.150
- Permeability is what you talk
about in this paper very much.

01:22:00.150 --> 01:22:05.190
Can I just ask you, as
we have only a minute

01:22:05.190 --> 01:22:08.440
to go, when you talk about
the third attractor there,

01:22:08.440 --> 01:22:10.900
you always give it--
you always also read it

01:22:10.900 --> 01:22:15.210
from an aesthetic point of
view, that the construction has

01:22:15.210 --> 01:22:16.310
to be beautiful.

01:22:16.310 --> 01:22:17.780
The construction has to be good.

01:22:17.780 --> 01:22:22.990
There's also there's
always that aesthetic idea,

01:22:22.990 --> 01:22:25.990
and I don't mean a aesthetisized
idea, but an aesthetic idea,

01:22:25.990 --> 01:22:30.620
an ethical idea, that is
part of your assumption

01:22:30.620 --> 01:22:32.780
about the way in
which things connect

01:22:32.780 --> 01:22:35.180
or the unfolding process.

01:22:35.180 --> 01:22:37.200
And as somebody
interested in aesthetics,

01:22:37.200 --> 01:22:42.540
I've always wondered about
it, the good construction,

01:22:42.540 --> 01:22:45.220
which you talk a lot
about in your book.

01:22:45.220 --> 01:22:51.890
- I did aesthetics as rendering
oneself sensitive to things.

01:22:51.890 --> 01:22:53.480
So for me, it would
be the aesthetic

01:22:53.480 --> 01:22:55.590
of science, which is the
instrument by which we

01:22:55.590 --> 01:22:59.710
begin to become sensitive
to, for example, a watershed.

01:22:59.710 --> 01:23:01.750
And there is the
aesthetic of politics,

01:23:01.750 --> 01:23:06.400
which is how do we hear the
voices, voices, so to speak,

01:23:06.400 --> 01:23:09.000
which is a rendering
sensitive to.

01:23:09.000 --> 01:23:10.940
And of course, there
is the aesthetic,

01:23:10.940 --> 01:23:13.900
which has been sort
of simplified or

01:23:13.900 --> 01:23:15.900
re-institutionalized
around the art,

01:23:15.900 --> 01:23:19.140
but of which the art are
not the only appropriator,

01:23:19.140 --> 01:23:23.540
nor the only maker,
which is very important.

01:23:23.540 --> 01:23:26.010
And I'm always interested
in these three aesthetics

01:23:26.010 --> 01:23:31.850
together, because
as Peter just said,

01:23:31.850 --> 01:23:35.670
it's very difficult to get out
of the notion of boundaries,

01:23:35.670 --> 01:23:38.680
borders, and so on,
without complete invention

01:23:38.680 --> 01:23:41.320
into some of them
come from [INAUDIBLE].

01:23:41.320 --> 01:23:42.840
I mean, this
beautiful piece you--

01:23:42.840 --> 01:23:45.920
I'm sorry for the horrible
view I gave of Sara Sze's work.

01:23:45.920 --> 01:23:48.280
But I think it's an absolutely
magnificent example,

01:23:48.280 --> 01:23:52.050
and I immediately sent it to my
friend Joe scientist in Paris

01:23:52.050 --> 01:23:53.660
and said, this
lady was an artist.

01:23:53.660 --> 01:23:56.150
And so, at least three
or four of a point

01:23:56.150 --> 01:23:58.610
we are trying to source
in our representation

01:23:58.610 --> 01:24:01.150
of a critical zone, precisely
because of the multiplicity

01:24:01.150 --> 01:24:02.960
and the non-boundedness of it.

01:24:02.960 --> 01:24:05.270
It's not bounded.

01:24:05.270 --> 01:24:06.340
Yet, you are in it.

01:24:06.340 --> 01:24:12.200
So she found my aesthetics,
a beautiful example

01:24:12.200 --> 01:24:13.700
of something we are
struggling with,

01:24:13.700 --> 01:24:16.856
the scientists I'm working with.

01:24:16.856 --> 01:24:19.700
- And also artists and also
writers, because language

01:24:19.700 --> 01:24:20.480
is not bounded.

01:24:20.480 --> 01:24:22.880
And we're always in
the middle of it.

01:24:22.880 --> 01:24:25.821
- Last week with Richard
Powers, the great novelist.

01:24:25.821 --> 01:24:27.820
I had the privilege of
spending a week with him,

01:24:27.820 --> 01:24:29.840
and he is writing a
book where the agent

01:24:29.840 --> 01:24:33.320
and the main
characters as trees.

01:24:33.320 --> 01:24:34.660
Again, where are the trees?

01:24:34.660 --> 01:24:36.890
In the forest, classical
question, [INAUDIBLE].

01:24:40.200 --> 01:24:42.490
One of his arguments
is that the bumper crop

01:24:42.490 --> 01:24:44.820
that we have today
of oaks coming here

01:24:44.820 --> 01:24:46.840
is actually
collective strategies

01:24:46.840 --> 01:24:51.312
of trees to find with their
competitors, so to speak.

01:24:51.312 --> 01:24:53.570
It's a very clever
trick of trees.

01:24:53.570 --> 01:24:54.436
I hope he is right.

01:24:54.436 --> 01:24:56.990
- Well, in these
Anthropocenic wars.

01:24:56.990 --> 01:25:00.600
Let's now turn to
some questions.

01:25:00.600 --> 01:25:01.830
There's a mic.

01:25:01.830 --> 01:25:03.450
Please line up.

01:25:03.450 --> 01:25:08.030
We have 10 minutes
for questions.

01:25:08.030 --> 01:25:11.680
- It's a great honor
to hear you all talk,

01:25:11.680 --> 01:25:14.050
not just you Professor
Latour, but all four of you.

01:25:14.050 --> 01:25:15.047
Thank you very much.

01:25:15.047 --> 01:25:16.380
My name is Jessica Gienow-Hecht.

01:25:16.380 --> 01:25:18.180
I hail from Berlin.

01:25:18.180 --> 01:25:20.950
I'll be your colleague
Professor Latour next semester

01:25:20.950 --> 01:25:23.220
for one term.

01:25:23.220 --> 01:25:26.630
I am afraid my question
is somewhat conventional.

01:25:26.630 --> 01:25:29.100
But what I wanted
to ask you is what

01:25:29.100 --> 01:25:32.510
do you do with the question
of power in your tale?

01:25:32.510 --> 01:25:34.500
I understand that
in your scheme,

01:25:34.500 --> 01:25:38.150
which is kind of a tripod,
you are urge us to pay more

01:25:38.150 --> 01:25:43.030
attention to the third
leg, the Earth, and yet,

01:25:43.030 --> 01:25:47.420
power so far has dictated that
most of us in our perception

01:25:47.420 --> 01:25:51.310
oscillate between the
palace and the globe,

01:25:51.310 --> 01:25:54.800
mostly because of questions of
power the nation state promises

01:25:54.800 --> 01:25:57.630
us, and that's its power to
solve the problems that we

01:25:57.630 --> 01:26:01.440
cannot solve ourselves, while
the globe exerts a power

01:26:01.440 --> 01:26:02.610
of attraction.

01:26:02.610 --> 01:26:06.140
There might be potential in
terms of mobility or employment

01:26:06.140 --> 01:26:08.690
or whatever that may
make things possible

01:26:08.690 --> 01:26:10.160
that we don't have access to.

01:26:10.160 --> 01:26:14.110
What is the power of the Earth
in order to make itself heard?

01:26:14.110 --> 01:26:16.340
You're appealing to our sense.

01:26:16.340 --> 01:26:19.590
- The power is attraction.

01:26:19.590 --> 01:26:21.905
It's a very interesting
question, because very sightly,

01:26:21.905 --> 01:26:27.650
there is something slightly
boring about the Earth,

01:26:27.650 --> 01:26:30.780
which is it doesn't-- it
has nothing spectacular.

01:26:30.780 --> 01:26:33.340
- Exactly, but how does the
Earth then brand itself?

01:26:33.340 --> 01:26:34.960
- Sorry?

01:26:34.960 --> 01:26:37.190
- How does the Earth
brand itself in

01:26:37.190 --> 01:26:40.350
order to develop a power of
attraction, which in your tale,

01:26:40.350 --> 01:26:41.950
is what it has to do?

01:26:41.950 --> 01:26:42.880
- I don't know.

01:26:42.880 --> 01:26:45.010
I mean, this is what
worries me a lot,

01:26:45.010 --> 01:26:47.190
because there was
something-- very something

01:26:47.190 --> 01:26:53.200
exciting about the globe,
very something nostalgically

01:26:53.200 --> 01:26:57.350
exciting about going back, even
towards an imaginary community.

01:26:57.350 --> 01:26:59.990
And there is something
precisely, [INAUDIBLE]

01:26:59.990 --> 01:27:05.870
word, earthly,
mundane, down to land.

01:27:05.870 --> 01:27:07.860
And there is
nothing spectacular.

01:27:07.860 --> 01:27:11.590
And also, that's the work
on the critical zone.

01:27:11.590 --> 01:27:15.630
It's extraordinarily
localized and idiosyncratic,

01:27:15.630 --> 01:27:17.320
because precisely,
we have to relearn

01:27:17.320 --> 01:27:22.202
the skills of as you
said, re-localizing

01:27:22.202 --> 01:27:23.160
many of these entities.

01:27:23.160 --> 01:27:24.576
It is very, very
difficult to have

01:27:24.576 --> 01:27:26.524
a sort of generalized
concept, which

01:27:26.524 --> 01:27:27.940
is exactly the
opposite of what we

01:27:27.940 --> 01:27:29.667
mean when we go to the globe.

01:27:29.667 --> 01:27:31.250
So I have no I have
no answer to that.

01:27:31.250 --> 01:27:33.690
It's a very worrying question.

01:27:33.690 --> 01:27:36.230
We all have to turn to something
which is less spectacular.

01:27:36.230 --> 01:27:39.050
Now, I have another version
of the same argument, which

01:27:39.050 --> 01:27:43.590
is the opposite, which
is to say, in one way,

01:27:43.590 --> 01:27:48.070
it's as extraordinarily
interesting and progressive

01:27:48.070 --> 01:27:56.140
than the old question of the
16th century discovery of land,

01:27:56.140 --> 01:28:00.890
new land, new land which I
had been-- when we destroyed

01:28:00.890 --> 01:28:02.790
the inhabitants first.

01:28:02.790 --> 01:28:06.080
So it has something about
the Age of Discovery,

01:28:06.080 --> 01:28:07.920
but it's not the
land in extension.

01:28:07.920 --> 01:28:10.507
It's not unfortunately
where we wiped out

01:28:10.507 --> 01:28:11.590
the people who were there.

01:28:11.590 --> 01:28:14.550
It's a land in intensity.

01:28:14.550 --> 01:28:19.450
And it has some sort
of the same fabulously

01:28:19.450 --> 01:28:24.690
interesting and troubling
meaning than the 16th century.

01:28:24.690 --> 01:28:26.950
I think there's lots of
reason why we associate now

01:28:26.950 --> 01:28:29.540
lots of things in music,
in art, in theater

01:28:29.540 --> 01:28:32.245
with the 16th century, because
there's something very similar.

01:28:32.245 --> 01:28:33.620
But of course,
it's not the land.

01:28:33.620 --> 01:28:37.430
It's not the discovery
of land res nullius.

01:28:37.430 --> 01:28:40.730
It's is the land where
we are all sharing

01:28:40.730 --> 01:28:42.661
the disappearance of the land.

01:28:42.661 --> 01:28:44.910
And this is a very interesting
element of anthropology

01:28:44.910 --> 01:28:47.500
now is that we learn
collectively what

01:28:47.500 --> 01:28:51.790
it is to have a land under
your feet disappearing.

01:28:51.790 --> 01:28:56.570
Before, it was precisely the
tragic discovery of those

01:28:56.570 --> 01:29:00.190
we had-- the land of
whom we had occupied.

01:29:00.190 --> 01:29:02.770
But now, it's something
which everybody in a way--

01:29:02.770 --> 01:29:05.420
it's a new universal
anthropology.

01:29:05.420 --> 01:29:09.360
So this is where power is.

01:29:09.360 --> 01:29:10.820
- Thank you very much.

01:29:10.820 --> 01:29:13.230
My name is a Ester Giftechein
from the Anthropology

01:29:13.230 --> 01:29:14.240
Department.

01:29:14.240 --> 01:29:20.800
My question is so how could we
think about the attractor three

01:29:20.800 --> 01:29:25.740
without the interruption of
the attractor one and two?

01:29:25.740 --> 01:29:31.080
What's your projection in that
regard, which the attractor

01:29:31.080 --> 01:29:35.190
one and attractor two, which
happen to be handicapped

01:29:35.190 --> 01:29:37.820
and biased in times of
the hierarchies they

01:29:37.820 --> 01:29:41.860
have been posing on
us all this time?

01:29:41.860 --> 01:29:48.600
What kind of a culture would
you project as emerging

01:29:48.600 --> 01:29:51.930
or would emerge in
the future in relation

01:29:51.930 --> 01:29:56.250
to networks and in relation
to what you defined

01:29:56.250 --> 01:29:59.570
as the attractor, what's your
concerns about that attractor

01:29:59.570 --> 01:30:00.610
three?

01:30:00.610 --> 01:30:01.120
Thank you.

01:30:01.120 --> 01:30:03.100
- Thank you.

01:30:03.100 --> 01:30:06.770
My definition of anthropology,
as you might know,

01:30:06.770 --> 01:30:10.760
is a diplomatic building,
diplomatic encounters,

01:30:10.760 --> 01:30:16.620
between basically conflicting
cosmologies, so to speak.

01:30:16.620 --> 01:30:18.890
So I'm fairly interested,
and your question

01:30:18.890 --> 01:30:21.540
is very interesting, because
what I'm trying to imagine

01:30:21.540 --> 01:30:27.213
is where instead of saying
globalization is gone

01:30:27.213 --> 01:30:30.830
or you should not try to
go back to the land of old,

01:30:30.830 --> 01:30:32.630
I think it's quite
interesting to see what

01:30:32.630 --> 01:30:36.360
other property to reopen the
discussion with those who

01:30:36.360 --> 01:30:40.700
are simultaneously repulsed
by the globe and attracted by

01:30:40.700 --> 01:30:41.200
[INAUDIBLE].

01:30:41.200 --> 01:30:42.900
What do they want?

01:30:42.900 --> 01:30:44.500
They want protection.

01:30:44.500 --> 01:30:45.690
We all want protection.

01:30:45.690 --> 01:30:48.440
It's not something which is
wrong to want protection.

01:30:48.440 --> 01:30:50.930
But protections is not
ensured by the rich--

01:30:50.930 --> 01:30:53.985
in the case of Brexit,
again, I'm obsessed by that.

01:30:53.985 --> 01:30:55.860
If there is one thing
which is absolutely not

01:30:55.860 --> 01:30:57.276
protected to England
is to go back

01:30:57.276 --> 01:30:59.860
to their little, boring island.

01:30:59.860 --> 01:31:05.940
So but they want protection
is a sensible thing to ask.

01:31:05.940 --> 01:31:08.590
And the same thing with the
negotiation about the globe.

01:31:08.590 --> 01:31:11.550
There was something absolutely
crucial in the globe.

01:31:11.550 --> 01:31:13.050
It is a multiplicity
of differences.

01:31:13.050 --> 01:31:15.091
But if you [INAUDIBLE]
the globe is the extension

01:31:15.091 --> 01:31:20.530
of the same set of cliched
and standardize indifference,

01:31:20.530 --> 01:31:22.520
it's a big chance.

01:31:22.520 --> 01:31:25.070
So what I'm trying to
imagine it is how can we

01:31:25.070 --> 01:31:28.900
build a political orientation,
the same thing which

01:31:28.900 --> 01:31:32.070
has been done in 19th century
with a social question?

01:31:32.070 --> 01:31:35.010
After all, we
invented with masses

01:31:35.010 --> 01:31:38.440
of people in the
social sciences,

01:31:38.440 --> 01:31:43.530
in activism, in religion, how
to handle the social question.

01:31:43.530 --> 01:31:45.560
The task now is
not more difficult,

01:31:45.560 --> 01:31:48.110
but it requires a
reorientation, because we

01:31:48.110 --> 01:31:51.610
have to deal precisely with
all this non-individualizing

01:31:51.610 --> 01:31:54.350
multiplicity, which we
share our existence.

01:31:54.350 --> 01:31:59.410
So that's what I mean by opening
a negotiation on this thing.

01:31:59.410 --> 01:32:03.810
- Two more quick
questions, thank you.

01:32:03.810 --> 01:32:07.600
- I'm Sam Smiley, artographer,
artist researcher, teacher.

01:32:07.600 --> 01:32:10.580
So I am kind of triangulating.

01:32:10.580 --> 01:32:13.800
So my question which may
have been sort of addressed

01:32:13.800 --> 01:32:18.300
in last one is what about
the question of asymmetries

01:32:18.300 --> 01:32:19.910
within the network?

01:32:19.910 --> 01:32:20.810
- Asymmetries?

01:32:20.810 --> 01:32:23.300
- Within the network.

01:32:23.300 --> 01:32:23.930
- Sorry?

01:32:23.930 --> 01:32:27.104
- Asymmetries
within the network.

01:32:27.104 --> 01:32:27.770
- What about it?

01:32:27.770 --> 01:32:28.630
Do you like it?

01:32:28.630 --> 01:32:29.760
- What do I like?

01:32:29.760 --> 01:32:34.056
- Do you like asymmetrical
relations within networks?

01:32:34.056 --> 01:32:36.650
Like it, or dislike
it, or neither?

01:32:36.650 --> 01:32:38.860
- Neither.

01:32:38.860 --> 01:32:40.800
I mean, the asymmetry
of networks,

01:32:40.800 --> 01:32:42.140
I'm not understanding.

01:32:42.140 --> 01:32:44.380
I mean, the asymmetry
is a different--

01:32:44.380 --> 01:32:46.460
it doesn't apply very
well to a network.

01:32:46.460 --> 01:32:47.970
But what do we mean, exactly?

01:32:47.970 --> 01:32:48.820
Can you develop?

01:32:48.820 --> 01:32:53.880
- Yeah, so within a
network, the power relations

01:32:53.880 --> 01:32:54.910
in between the objects.

01:32:58.442 --> 01:33:02.594
It could be about power,
asymmetric relations.

01:33:02.594 --> 01:33:04.260
- Always there are
asymmetric relations.

01:33:04.260 --> 01:33:06.400
What would be a
symmetrical relation?

01:33:06.400 --> 01:33:07.380
I don't understand.

01:33:07.380 --> 01:33:10.610
Where would it be a place
where there's no power?

01:33:10.610 --> 01:33:12.320
What would be a
non-powered relation.

01:33:12.320 --> 01:33:14.640
I need to understand
your question.

01:33:14.640 --> 01:33:18.660
- I guess I'm making the
assumption that it was a power.

01:33:18.660 --> 01:33:21.580
It was that bringing
asymmetries out

01:33:21.580 --> 01:33:24.220
defines what you just described.

01:33:24.220 --> 01:33:26.130
- I'm not sure I understand.

01:33:26.130 --> 01:33:28.180
In all of this
question of ecology,

01:33:28.180 --> 01:33:30.100
we have to understand
we are at war.

01:33:30.100 --> 01:33:31.260
It's war.

01:33:31.260 --> 01:33:34.950
So the question of
power is everywhere.

01:33:34.950 --> 01:33:38.310
The pseudo controversy
about the climate,

01:33:38.310 --> 01:33:42.700
anthropic origin of climate,
is a declaration of war.

01:33:42.700 --> 01:33:44.820
The word negationist
has been used, I think,

01:33:44.820 --> 01:33:45.570
with good reason.

01:33:45.570 --> 01:33:46.528
It's a question of war.

01:33:46.528 --> 01:33:49.700
We don't want to live in
the country where you live.

01:33:49.700 --> 01:33:52.980
So the question of territory
and what we occupy a territory

01:33:52.980 --> 01:33:57.790
is completely suffused
with power everywhere.

01:33:57.790 --> 01:34:01.710
And the problem of this third
attractor is that, of course,

01:34:01.710 --> 01:34:04.670
it's slightly
boring, which is one

01:34:04.670 --> 01:34:06.990
of the prime sort of
statistic, as you say,

01:34:06.990 --> 01:34:10.590
and it's also an absolutely
major question of war

01:34:10.590 --> 01:34:12.150
and peace.

01:34:12.150 --> 01:34:17.394
So if this was behind your
question, yes, we are at war.

01:34:17.394 --> 01:34:19.060
- That's why I
emphasized the negativity

01:34:19.060 --> 01:34:20.670
of the third attractor.

01:34:20.670 --> 01:34:23.110
The last question.

01:34:23.110 --> 01:34:26.840
- Hi, I'm Fernando Rosenberg, a
teacher at Brandeis University.

01:34:26.840 --> 01:34:30.850
One notion that I haven't heard
in the discussion of the panel

01:34:30.850 --> 01:34:32.600
is the notion of rights.

01:34:32.600 --> 01:34:34.370
And I want rights.

01:34:34.370 --> 01:34:37.100
And I wonder,
because the Bolivian

01:34:37.100 --> 01:34:41.660
and the Ecuadorian constitutions
recognize the rights of nature.

01:34:41.660 --> 01:34:43.350
And this is a very
problematic notion

01:34:43.350 --> 01:34:45.370
that has been widely discussed.

01:34:45.370 --> 01:34:47.810
But I wonder if
you see any future

01:34:47.810 --> 01:34:52.930
for a universal declaration
of non-human rights

01:34:52.930 --> 01:34:59.380
or post-human rights in which
what are the entities that

01:34:59.380 --> 01:35:01.260
to which these
rights are recognized

01:35:01.260 --> 01:35:03.600
is defined on a
case-by-case basis.

01:35:03.600 --> 01:35:07.609
- Well, I think here we
need a ritual to Pachamama.

01:35:07.609 --> 01:35:09.900
That would be the polite way
of answering the question.

01:35:09.900 --> 01:35:11.720
Let's have a ritual.

01:35:11.720 --> 01:35:15.310
And Pachamama, of course,
is a very interesting figure

01:35:15.310 --> 01:35:17.020
introduced into
the constitution.

01:35:17.020 --> 01:35:20.450
I think this constitutional
invention will multiply.

01:35:20.450 --> 01:35:26.680
But it's not us who attribute an
agency to Pachamama or to Gaia.

01:35:26.680 --> 01:35:29.810
It's Gaia which is coming
to us and requesting,

01:35:29.810 --> 01:35:32.750
and we bow to this
sort of not exactly

01:35:32.750 --> 01:35:35.584
authority or sovereignty, but
something which is certainly

01:35:35.584 --> 01:35:37.000
something, which
even in the Paris

01:35:37.000 --> 01:35:39.180
was amazing in this sense.

01:35:39.180 --> 01:35:44.630
These people were not assembled
by the horizon of modernization

01:35:44.630 --> 01:35:45.900
and the global modernization.

01:35:45.900 --> 01:35:47.483
They were assembled
by something which

01:35:47.483 --> 01:35:51.190
were impacting on all of
them in a strange way.

01:35:51.190 --> 01:35:54.736
So in a way, we have
already these figures,

01:35:54.736 --> 01:35:58.210
which is not in
any constitution,

01:35:58.210 --> 01:36:01.800
but it is weighing
on us in a way.

01:36:01.800 --> 01:36:04.270
And that's where I think
all of this invention where

01:36:04.270 --> 01:36:07.901
there is a declaration against
ecocide now working everywhere.

01:36:07.901 --> 01:36:09.400
There are people
in this country who

01:36:09.400 --> 01:36:11.670
have attacked their government
for not-- in Holland,

01:36:11.670 --> 01:36:15.900
I'm sorry, for not actually
protecting the environment.

01:36:15.900 --> 01:36:16.930
So this will multiply.

01:36:16.930 --> 01:36:19.820
Lawyers are rich
since the famous paper

01:36:19.820 --> 01:36:22.160
by Stone many, many years ago.

01:36:22.160 --> 01:36:24.770
The law is as often
very much in advance

01:36:24.770 --> 01:36:26.330
of many of the
philosophical concepts

01:36:26.330 --> 01:36:27.663
